  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Support to Sustainable and Impoved Veterinary Services in Southern Afghanistan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Livestock owners</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Mercy Corps&#x2019; program aims to increase livestock production through greater access to information, services and quality medicines and equipment. Mercy Corps has designed this initiative using local expertise and experience learned in previous activities. Mercy Corps is using an approach that increases local government capacity in animal health coupled with functioning local veterinary field units (VFU) along with co-operative and supportive university service to have significant impact upon livestock production and hence contribute towards reducing poverty and food insecurity in southern Afghanistan. In order to reach out to the maximum number of final beneficiaries, Mercy Corps&#x2019; program predominantly targets the institutions which will serve livestock owners and their households. The target groups are the Provincial Veterinary Departments in Kandahar, Helmand, Uruzgan and Daikundi, the VFU Cooperative and its extension workers, and Kandahar University veterinary faculty and students. By strengthening the technical and managerial capacity of animal health service providers, Mercy Corps&#x2019; program is building sustainable, lasting sector support mechanisms in the troubled southern region of Afghanistan. The final beneficiaries of the program are ultimately the livestock owners across the target provinces. The overall objective of the program is to improve rural livelihoods and food security through increased livestock based incomes. The Specific Objective of the program is to increase farmer livestock productivity through greater access to best herd management practices, disease outbreak information, veterinary services and quality medicines and equipment.</narrative>
  </description>
